This happens because Java is pass by value: When calling a method, the values of the arguments are copied to the local variables in the parameter list of the called method. 

This appears to not happen with `bunnyName`. That is because `bunnyName` is a `String`, which is a reference type.  The counters are primitives. 

With reference types, what gets passed to a called method is a copy of the reference. The local variable in the called method becomes an alias for the corresponding variable doing the calling. Within the called method, as long as the local reference variable isn&#39;t changed to point to something else, what happens to it in the called method also happens to it in the calling method. 

